column1: 309000;instagram;2018-10-07 12:54:46;FALSE;"a pit forms in my stomach and tears well up in my eyes as i read the headline ""brett kavanaugh sworn in as supreme court justice"". it's not an if or a maybe
column2: it's a fact. and that kills me. it kills me to know that a man with blatant disregard for a woman's body will now sit on the highest court in america. it kills me because i don't feel safe.

column1: i have been sexually assaulted. on more than one occasion and to varying degrees. i can't actually bring myself to say the r word because i'm afraid of what people would think of me. i'm afraid they would tell me i was too drunk or i chose to hang out with that guy
column2: so it's my fault. the guilt that a survivor carries is so heavy it can be crippling and it can affect every decision they make going forward.

column1: i say these things because i'm so afraid that we live in a society that right now has said women don't matter. their voices don't matter. their stories don't matter. their bodies don't matter. i'm crying as i write this because i can't stop thinking about dr. ford and the millions of women who speak up about rape and sexual assault who are then told ""it doesn't matter."" i am trying so hard to keep faith in people
column2: but it is so fucking hard when stories like the kavanaugh trial come up and are plastered everywhere. when the victimhood of men is wielded like a weapon against survivors
column3: i feel hot with anger and resolve. -

column1: i'm not backing down and i'm not giving up. i am fucking angry and heartbroken. but i'm not going to keep quiet or slink off to the shadows like so many people would like me too. i'm going to take the hands of my sisters
column3: and i'm going to yell and scream our stories. i know the power of a collective. i know the power of community. i am scared and i am angry
column4: but i'm not fucking going anywhere. none of us are. just because you tell us our voices don't matter doesn't mean we'll ever stop using them.
and weinsteins of the world: women are watching and women are listening. we are planning and we are organizing. we are gathering in forces stronger than you've ever seen. we are not.going.anywhere.

column1: 309010;instagram;2018-10-07 12:58:30;FALSE;"family is a life jacket in the stormy sea of life.”― j.k. rowling
these men in my life made me a strong
column2: independent and passionate person. a father who gave me wings of independence
column3: a brother who treated me like a warrior princess and a husband who nourishes my confidence. these men shaped my being and i know has my back at any given point of time.

column1: i wish everyone celebrates the men in their lives. its them who will emancipate the next generation of men and have power to influence the ones who are corrupting the present. equality and safety is not about being against or looking down on men but more about celebrating the heroes in our lives and giving them the power to combat the pain of endless harassments and hatred.
a big shout out to all those beautiful fathers
column3: friends and partners who regularly voice their opinion against the norm and are the biggest cheerleaders of their fearless women.  #metoo #empoweringmen #familygoals";;en;#metoo

column1: 309040;instagram;2018-10-07 12:30:00;FALSE;"there are so many reasons why october is my favorite month and the hardest month for me.

this is my first autumn back in tennessee since 2013. things here are completely different from oregon. it is amazing how the same country can house so many climates. this is where i’m from and on some level i feel i have a responsibility to this place- on the other hand

column2: i guess i’m just saying if you’re back in your little home town or you never left it
column3: you can actively work to make it better rather than shriveling up and wishing you could leave (though
column4: i’ve done plenty of that). it is true there are good people everywhere if you look and that’s definitely not my point here. small town culture is both a blessing and a burden.

column1: i think the worst is hearing people everywhere talk about false reporting as if it’s a thing that happens often. it isn’t. that all this me too stuff is just political and why didn’t ford report her assault before. and there’s no way to have a conversation about this without disclosing #metoo. then
column2: i’m at risk of being emotional which then is used against me. well
column4: therefore you’re not being logical. and minds aren’t changed more than half the time. over and over i found that exposing my trauma only wounds me over again and people who needs to listen plug up their ears because it’s too uncomfortable to deal with or they’re guilty of semi- consensual or coerced sex. •

column1: i have written this before and i’ll write it again and probably again in the future. i did report my sexual assault in 2012. days within it happening. nothing happened. i had to give a very difficult statement. a few people who were at the party had to be interviewed. that’s it. the person who did it is living his life as if he’s not a rapist. i have mutual friends who continue to support him. i had friends at the time not believe me and blame me (really interesting how an incapacitated person could be at fault but okay). i am tired. i’m tired of evil winning. i’m tired of survivors being believed(trust me
column2: i’d rather it not be true). i’m tired of living in the “best country” that doesn’t prioritize us. cont.";;en;#metoo.;;;;;0;;motherwrites;naomi;;0;False;4;0;0;58;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/ee7144139bdf80843708af892dae3242/5D1441C8/t51.2885-15/e35/42002635_470047223403220_9197256660763995099_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"there are so many reasons why october is my favorite month and the hardest month for me.

column1: i did not report him because i did not have the energy to fight for my humanity in court. i did not call the police because i was afraid of men. i did not report him because i wanted to believe it wasn't what it was
column2: that he couldn't possibly be capable of what happened. i did not report him because the first person i called for help said ""well
column3: what did you expect to happen?"" i did not report him because it broke me
column4: and i did not have the energy to fight for anything except staying alive. i am still fighting. i did not report him because a christian friend told me i needed to forgive him
column5: and then pushed me to confront him and forgive him to his face. i did not report him because i valued his life over my own. i did not want to ""ruin"" it. i felt empathy. for him.

column1: i didn't report him because i still have trouble believing myself
column2: because he explained that ""it was not what it looked like"" or what it felt like. i did not report him because he said he was sorry and because i did not have the ability to feel anymore about anything. i did not report him because he was someone i cared about
column4: still want to believe this was all just some misunderstanding. but i cannot.

column1: due process is cool and all
column2: but have you ever been raped? no? then shut the fuck up. i know who is standing for those of us who survived
column3: and who is not. i see you.

column2: angry that this entire past year i've had to relive trauma i want to forget
column3: angry that people don't believe dr. ford
column4: angry that people think there's only one way of reacting to rape or attempted rape
column5: angry that people think they own or are entitled to say anything about how one survives or chooses to survive. rape is a kind of murder. i survived not because it is survivable
column6: but because i am the strongest person i know. that's the truth.

column4: an eager anticipation woke us up in our brooklyn loft unusually early. with our hearts racing
column5: we tuned into the hearings of dr. christine blasey ford and judge brett kavanaugh.

column1: amidst dr. ford’s emotionally brave testimony
column3: and an amalgamation of statements from an assembly of both incredibly compassionate and unbelievably ruthless senators
column4: we made a new song. and it was for her.

column2: we began putting a video together to more fully capture the inspiration behind this song. we wanted to point to women
column3: from a range of walks of life
column4: women who have taken a stance when it wasn’t necessarily easy to do so. our goal was to highlight the courage it takes to call something out loud and to stand up tall when the odds may not be in our favor.

column1: the women in this piece are just a few among many who inspire us to continue to use our voices and demand to be heard. the conclusory chorus lyric “never look back again” doesn’t imply we shouldn’t look back on the women who have taught us how to lead the way — we most absolutely should — but that we should always move bravely into the future. we hope with our song to thank the women who have empowered us so selflessly and perhaps to inspire those still searching to find their strengths.
see the full video for “her” now — link in bio.
music and lyrics by gracie and rachel @gracieandrachel
co-written and co-produced by garrett eaton @the_name_is_dame

column1: the women in this piece are just a few among many who inspire us to continue to use our voices and demand to be heard. the conclusory chorus lyric “never look back again” doesn’t imply we shouldn’t look back on the women who have taught us how to lead the way — we most absolutely should — but that we should always move bravely into the future. we hope with our song to thank the women who have empowered us so selflessly and perhaps to inspire those still searching to find their strengths.

column1: 309132;instagram;2018-10-07 11:48:20;FALSE;“why did she wait so long” “women should report the assault” this is why women are too afraid to come forward. these are only two examples of the system failing us. how would you feel finally having the courage to come forward about the most traumatizing thing to happen to you only to be shut down and see your attacker get off with barely a slap on the wrist? or to be 12 and get the courage to finally trust someone enough to tell them about the abuse you suffered for years and get that memory out of the “box” and relive every second of every time only for police to tell you “he’s under 18” “he’s exploring” or to have your entire family hate you for ruining his imagine. and the best one yet

column1: 309142;instagram;2018-10-07 10:56:10;FALSE;"you may write me down in history
you may trod me in the very dirt
why are you beset with gloom?
cause i walk like i’ve got oil wells
just like moons and like suns
did you want to see me broken?
don’t you take it awful hard
cause i laugh like i’ve got gold mines
you may shoot me with your words
you may cut me with your eyes
you may kill me with your hatefulness
does it come as a surprise
that i dance like i’ve got diamonds
at the meeting of my thighs?
out of the guts of history’s shame
up from a past that’s rooted in pain
welling and swelling i beat the tide.
leaving behind nights of terror and fear
bringing gifts that my ancestors gave
i am the dream and the hope of the slave.

column2: this is not our first rodeo!

column1: 309153;instagram;2018-10-07 11:01:53;FALSE;"i'm really happy to see ""cholita's rise"" in the new edition of @terramatermag . it gives me particular joy that this story has been picked up by several publications since the purpose of doing it was to highlight the path to the emancipation of these women and hopefully inspire more to do the same.
when i started working on the project
column2: i was far from imagining that the weinstein scandal and the #metoo movement will exist
column3: but during that period i was working i heard some stories that resemble to what later came to light. others were different
column4: but they all had one common thing
column5: women were subjected to violence or mistreatment
column6: fewer opportunities than men and often ignored by society and the people with the highest responsibilities in the country.

column2: after seeing what happened with the kavanaugh nomination
column3: i felt really angry and disappointed. not that i was expecting a different final
column4: since its well documented what is going on in trumpland
column5: but somehow i was still hoping that there was still some dignity and responsibility in some of the most powerful people on the planet.

column2: this project transformed me in ways i never imagined and slowly made me more aware of how unfair women are being treated. maybe i knew but like many
column3: maybe i wasn't paying enough attention to it
column4: and saying this i know it shouldn't serve as an excuse. so i want to thank all the women that helped me by telling their story and for making me see more clearly. i may have started this project but it is all yours.

column1: doing the documentary about indian women was definetely the biggest project of my year and i'm really glad that this is actually happening! i just finished 'version1' right before my yoga teacher training and i can say that it just has been an incredible journey for me.

i want to show that there is more to the topuc than we can hear and see in the news. just receiving horrible stories undermines the hard work and every day fights of indian women to live a more independent life.

column7: do voiceovers and struggling with indian sounds was an amazing experience and i have never thought that this will really happening - at least not in this quality and quantity.

column1: version1 is now a little bit longer than 60min. when i get back to germany (very soon) i will do some more work on it and do the feinschliff.
and then soon i have to find a way to get people to watch all this. so if you have any contacts to media houses
column4: etc just message me and help me distribute it to a broader audience.

column1: 309158;instagram;2018-10-07 11:06:42;FALSE;"die neuigkeiten über brett kavanaugh haben mich gestern mit absoluter fassungslosigkeit und einem gefühl von hilflosigkeit zurückgelassen.
es hat mich nicht überrascht. und dennoch macht es mich wütend
column2: dass wir immer noch in einer welt leben
column3: in der die stimme einer frau nichts wert ist.

column2: dass solche anschuldigungen das leben eines mannes ruinieren würden
column3: und jetzt sitzt kavanaugh lebenslang auf dem richterstuhl des supreme courts.

column2: dass frauen ihre vergewaltigungen nicht früher melden? überhaupt melden? auch wenn dies in den usa passiert
column3: mein vertrauen in das system ist erschüttert. hierzulande ist zwar die judikative unabhängiger von der politik
column4: aber dennoch sehe ich mich jeden tag mit menschen konfrontiert
column7: dass ein „so netter mann“ ein vergewaltiger sein könnte.

column1: ich habe es satt. ich bin wütend. und da soll mir niemand erzählen
column2: dass ich mal runterkommen soll. ich kann dafür einfach keine toleranz mehr aufbringen.

column1: ich schreibe hier in der hoffnung viele zu erreichen. an alle männer da draußen: bitte sensibilisiert euch für die erfahrung von frauen. bitte überdenkt machtstrukturen im system. bitte überdenkt euer eigenes verhalten. dies gilt auch für frauen: bitte haltet zueinander. bitte gebt nicht der internalisierten frauenfeindlichkeit nach
column2: die ihr mit euch rumschleppt. wir können nur etwa ändern

column1: 309178;instagram;2018-10-06 20:34:04;FALSE;"приехав в бельгию с двумя чемоданами одежды(в одном из них еще и швейная машинка была)
column2: я надеялась на возможность без труда пополнять свой гардероб здесь

column4: особых дресс кодов не придерживался и легко обходился джинсами на все случаи жизни. буквально через пару дней после приезда на нашу голову свалилось приглашение на святое причастие с торжественным ужином в замке(что было жирно подчеркнуто в пригласительной открытке). и тут я запаниковала. любимые джинсы отпадали сразу. платьев в моем гардеробе уже несколько лет как не наблюдалось. надо было срочно совершать набег на магазины.

column1: после дня мотания по шопинг-центрам я впала в такую глубокую депрессию
column2: что до сих пор ощущаю ее присутствие в те редкие 2 раза в год
column3: когда я рискую отправиться на поиски новой кофточки или куртки.

column2: блузки и юбки ""прощай молодость"" вызвали у меня стойкое желание испытать приступ мигрени ровно за час до начала церемонии причастия и остаться дома под благоговидным предлогом.
я отправилась плакаться на плече у мужа
column3: который страшно удивился моим пустым рукам и кислой физиономии. он-то уже рисовал себе кошмарную картину
column5: сгибаясь под тяжестью пакетов и коробок с моими обновками
column7: а потом тщетно пытается запихнуть ворох покупок в багажник.

column1: ситуацию в тот раз удалось спасти моим привезенным с собой ""набором для собеседований""-черной юбкой-карандашом и строгой

column2: но покупка одежды здесь так и осталась для меня проблемой. я не готова отдавать сотни и тысячи евро за вещь из бутика. не вижу в этом смысла. магазины же типа h&m или zara рассчитаны
column4: на подростков и людей с идеальной фигурой. ну и на тех
column7: который меня периодически выручает интересными обновками. хотя там тоже есть свои проблемы: попадание в размер
column9: да и просто сайты-обманки. но у меня до сих пор

column1: nobel prize 2018: nobel medicine prize goes to james p allison and tasaku honjo

the nobel medicine or physiology prize has been awarded to james p allison and tasaku honjo “for their discovery of cancer therapy by inhibition of negative immune regulation.”. this is for the first time that no literature prize will be given in 70 years because of a #metoo scandal.
the nobel prize in physiology or medicine was awarded by the nobel assembly at karolinska institutet

the nobel medicine or physiology prize has been awarded to james p allison and tasaku honjo “for their discovery of cancer therapy by inhibition of negative immune regulation.”. this is for the first time that no literature prize will be given in 70 years because of a  scandal.
the nobel prize in physiology or medicine was awarded by the nobel assembly at karolinska institutet

column1: 309188;instagram;2018-10-07 10:18:49;FALSE;"17名の一般人の支配被害経験談集📖
初めて知った単語 #マニピュレーター →配偶者や恋人の心を支配したいという欲求が異常に強い人。
タイトルはお父さんが支配者な時のケース集ですが、お父さん＝元少年・成年＝おじいちゃん＝男性＝元恋人＝夫＝親＝ビジネスパーソン なので、この立ち位置出身or現役で配置役割の都合ゆえの怒りが生じた時になりますね。
ミルキーの経験上、学歴スペック関係なしに怒りっぽい男性はハイエネルギーなビジネスパフォーマンスを披露する人が多いと思います。利益が入る際は妙に心の暖かい善人顔なことが一緒に働いても伺えており、こちらの本の中にも「内面と外面の違い」というキーワードがありました。はたして怒りを原動力に稼ぐということなのか?いずれにしろ自分に有利な状況を作り出す手段として、柔らかそうな人間に怒っているように見えます。
被害者は、とにかく真に受けない技術、すなわち不動心を発達させて身を守るべし。

column1: she writes: "" rage is probably too light of a term for how millions of women (and hopefully men) felt watching the farce of a hearing for the us supreme court nominee brett kavanaugh this week. i know it was a palpable heat emanating from my temples. we have seen that experiences we have a girls/boys affect us for the rest of our lives
column2: both they way we treat others and the ways we are treated. the enormity of the responses
column3: the outpouring from women and girls saying #metoo and laying bare of wounds upon the public and political altar was both empowering and so very distressing. this was summed up for me by the three teenage girls
column7: who wrote an open letter to dr. ford in a http://change.org petition

column3: with your whole life ahead of you
column4: and we see ourselves. our hearts break for the fifteen-year-old girl who walked in
column5: and how different that girl was who walked out. we feel connected to the 15-year-old girl still living inside of you
column6: and are outraged by the seventeen-year-old boy still living inside of him.” the poignance of being 15 and having to understand these things is not lost on any of us.""

giving birth after trauma can be an incredibly harrowing experience. published research is scant and few medical providers receive training in trauma-sensitive care. thanks to childbirth educator @penny.simkin (author of ""when survivors give birth"") and new programs like the signature strong start for mothers and newborns in st. louis
column3: things are starting to change. we have a long way to go but
column5: we'll get there. if anyone in this community has resources you can share
column6: wherever you are in the world

column1: 309264;instagram;2018-10-07 08:56:32;FALSE;"when i was about 14 a stranger called my phone and when i picked up he told me he had to tell me a secret my parents couldn’t know of. he then started describing sexual practices to me. completely unprompted. i hung up. nothing happened.
neither did anything happen to the guy who kept touching me at the bar 3 years ago and would not stop after i repeatedly asked him to
column2: except that he got kicked out. he did the same thing to me a year later at the same bar.

column1: nothing happened to the man who grabbed my butt while i was waiting for the train or the one who did it while i passed him on the street. i only looked at the one sharply who went out of his way to touched my butt at a fair i attended with friends.
i don’t talk about these instances much because i have learned ‘they happen’. they happen to me
column2: they happen to my friends and family. they happened to so many women i know. they happen all the time. anywhere. they just happen. but they should not happen and that is why so many brave women are starting to come forward with their traumatic stories.

column1: over the past couple of days there has been a lot of talk about the validity and authenticity of accusations and statements made by survivors of sexual assault. there are a few things i need to say about this:
1. if it seems unreasonably many women have such stories to tell
column2: that is because it happens too damn unreasonably often!

column1: 2. you do not get fame or fortune from being a victim of sexual assault. not even when the perpetrator is famous.
3. it is incredibly hard coming to terms with traumatic events
column2: let alone share them with others or even the entire fucking world on live television!

column1: if this sounds like i have gone mad - good
column2: because i hope i have. this cannot stay the status quo. i am mad. i am angry. i am furious. and i am only a small force in this storm of social justice. be afraid
column4: who got away with this shit for way too long
column5: we are coming for you - to be held accountable finally! #metoo #believesurvivors #ibelieveher #feministbitch #nastywoman";;en;#metoo

column1: 309265;instagram;2018-10-07 08:56:44;FALSE;"when i was 14 i woke up in the middle of the night to my mother screaming my name. i bolted out of bed and flung open her door to find her boyfriend brutally beating and raping her. he jumped off her and flung me out of the room and into a wall where i hit my head so hard i was dazed. he locked the door behind him and continued to abuse my mother. i pounded on the door freaking out i ran out of the apartment and pounded on our neighbors door screaming for help. no help came. i ran back to her room and screamed for him to stop. i should have called the cops i know but i was so focused on getting in that room. the door slowly opened and my mother slowly walked out took me to my room were she laid on the floor and went to sleep. i couldn't get her to climb into my bed or to let me  call for help.
5 years ago i too was asulted and i understood why my mother wouldn't let me call the police.

column1: i took this picture two years ago this month...right around the time i was raped. now i’ve deleted pretty much all the photos i took the actual night i was raped because they were just too painful to look back at. in fact

column1: so it was at this halloween party. i was dressed up as jessica rabbit so obviously it had to be a sexy costume. it’s not exactly unheard of to dress sexy for halloween the least i could do was not be generic. i was with a group of friends i knew pretty well. we saw this comedy show and i knew one of the guys in the show so we got invited to their after party
column3: i certainly drank more than i should have but when i look back on it now i have a hunch that i might have been drugged because i do remember asking one of my best guy friends at the time to hold my beer for me while i used the bathroom. i don’t remember a ton after i came out and took the beer back. it was my third drink so i was definitely tipsy already but honestly who even cares now? whether i was drugged or not doesn’t change what happened. anyway
column4: i started to feel sick and the same best guy friend who held my beer...let’s call him ted...was the designated driver who took me and our other friends home
column5: meaning he was 100% sober. i was the last person he dropped off and at this point i was blacking out so i didn’t know where i was. i thought i was in my house. i drifted off to sleep on the floor as i felt him kissing me. there’s pretty much just gaps in my memory the rest of the night (well there’s gaps in my memory of the whole night but you get the point). i remember ted’s voice whispering in my ear that he was in love with me and why did i have to have a bf why wasn’t i with him instead? i don’t like getting into the nitty gritty of what he actually did to me

column1: sample of shit my brother has said to me:
• “if she doesn’t remember how she got to the party or who was there
column2: how can we be sure she remembers the assault?”

column1: • “now any man can be attacked with false accusations without evidence and have his life destroyed.”
• “why didn’t she report it at the time to get justice
column2: if it was really that bad?”

column1: • “why do women walk alone at night? that’s just personal safety: men get assaulted too.”
as i prepare to report the first assault i experienced
column2: the one which has taken me 20 years to name and process
column3: these attitudes cut me to the bone. they are why we don’t report and
column5: why reporting does not even feel like an option... and the pain caused by this ignorance is harming survivors everywhere right now.

column1: these messages are clear: our bodies do not matter
column3: our emotions are not valid. our trauma feels thrust under the microscope of public scrutiny. it’s not perpetrators who stand accused today: it’s us. and amidst this pain we are pressured not only to advocate for ourselves
column4: but to become public educators about the effects of trauma on the brain
column6: and the historical and cultural barriers to justice faced by women and marginalised people.

column1: it’s so hard to hold my head up and keep fighting through this moment. my gratitude to all the wonderful people posting messages of love and light and stillness and rage
column2: reminding me that it’s okay to stop. it’s okay to feel the fatigue deep in your soul and succumb to despair for this moment... but this moment shall pass. we have survived worse than this.

column2: the numerous sexual assault allegations and the kavanaugh debacle
column3: women used to be harrassed in silence
column4: without a single soul protesting. as a movie buff
column5: i looked back for a second
column6: trying to remember a single hollywood film that portrays sexual harrassment in the workplace...i found one and one only. hollywood has been oblivious of this thorny subject because the whole system is rotten
column7: and hollywood prefers not to acknowledge the big elephant in the room. thankfully
column8: things are changing slowly but efficiently. the movie in question is a small independent gem called ""north country"" and it stars charlize theron as coal miner josey aimes who decided to bring her sexual harrassment case to court. it's one of the best movies of 2005 that earned ms theron an oscar nomination
column9: but it seems the film as well as the lesson learned from it have faded away in history.

column2: but i'm also worried that this whole me too movement may ruin many lives and families because some women might feel bitter. there's two sides to every story
column3: that's why women should arm themselves with evidence or at least report the harrassment as soon as possible.

column1: 309385;instagram;2018-10-07 07:21:18;FALSE;this is me after learning that we have a new supreme court justice who sexually assaulted someone. today i decided to break my silence. i have kept my rape inside since 2006. until now. apparently if you’re sexually assaulted it’s not that big of a deal. if you don’t remember every second of that assault you’re not telling the truth. guess what - i sure don’t remember it play by play. i remember waking up unable to move. i remember the next morning seeing a pile of pills and when asked about it he said i should leave. i remember me not wanting to say anything because i was ashamed. if you aren’t angry - get angry. if you’re not registered to vote - register. and if you’re not mad then god dammit get mad. #metoo #novemberiscoming #kavanaugh #dorriansredhand #dorrians;;en;#metoo

column2: i was molested by this coward ""lance (robert foste)"" when i was 6 years old. the second video is the first time i confronted him. i had to share this with my followers : some say i made this look easy but it wasn't. it was in no way easy but had to be done. so that this can give other children a voice who are afraid to speak. now that i am a grown woman and after many years of suffering

column2: this shouldn't stop the #brave women from coming forward about the trauma they have faced. this is the start of a movement and we should all work together to make sure that their voices are heard. .

column2: dark times. i have felt myself in dr. ford. i feel every woman’s despair. having spoken up about being a sexual assault survivor
column3: knowing everything that is at stake
column4: knowing you will be ridiculed and blamed and marked. doing it because you believe you must do it. because if you don’t
column5: it might kill you from within. watching the consequences & wondering why you bothered to let yourself be vulnerable- why? for men to mock you
column6: angry that you dared to speak up because you might shine a light on their own questionable behaviors? for women to minimize your trauma because they’ve minimized their own for so long & your voice awakens a deeply entrenched pain they wanted to forget? why? why do we speak up? to watch them slapping each other on the backs as brave survivors bellow “shame” through the senate halls? it feels like it was all in vain. sometimes
column7: my deepest regret in life is that i ever spoke up about what happened to me. but i’ve changed my mind. as i’ve seen so many women come forward & share what happened to them
column8: i am proud to be among them. do i make some of you uncomfortable? is it an inconvenience or a burden? so be it.  the victory of these hideous
column9: old white men is short-lived. they are afraid to their bones. every predator
column11: every misogynist knows we are in a moment of reckoning & their days are numbered. as i lie awake
column12: i can feel my heart beating hard. it strains with my overactive fight or flight response (a gift of trauma.) and that heart is chanting: “me-too. me-too. me-too.” be quiet
column13: men. listen. you will hear that sound in every woman around you. it is getting louder all the time.

column1: 309477;instagram;2018-10-07 05:49:11;FALSE;"if ever there was a day to don shell headphones and try to drown it all out
column2: this is it. get that mona lisa composure
column3: get calm and courageous and head back out. this week has hit many survivors of sexual assault hard
column4: including many people in your life that you many not have known to have this experience in their past. be kind to them
column5: allow them their anger and despair. watch the fabulous episode of #youcantaskthatabctv on survivors of sexual assault
column6: both female and male. hear those courageous folks talk about the variety of their experiences and responses. we are all around you and we’ve just seen one of our worst fears play out - that we are forced to voice our trauma and are shamed and disbelieved and harassed and ridiculed and it didn’t make a bit of difference anyway. the good news is that a solidarity of survivors and our allies is emerging and in those circles we are learning to voice our stories without shame. thanks to the folks in my life who have been there to listen this week. if you don’t have such people in your life
column8: there is no obligation to be confessional with the folks you know or in public
column9: there are lots of resources available where you can seek help anonymously. just know that you are not alone.

column18: including many people in your life that you many not have known to have this experience in their past. be kind to them
column19: allow them their anger and despair. watch the fabulous episode of #youcan notaskthatabctv on survivors of sexual assault
column20: both female and male. hear those courageous folks talk about the variety of their experiences and responses. we are all around you and we’ve just seen one of our worst fears play out - that we are forced to voice our trauma and are shamed and disbelieved and harassed and ridiculed and it didn’t make a bit of difference anyway. the good news is that a solidarity of survivors and our allies is emerging and in those circles we are learning to voice our stories without shame. thanks to the folks in my life who have been there to listen this week. if you don’t have such people in your life

column1: 309482;instagram;2018-10-07 05:50:38;FALSE;time and time again although it has been 13 years. i still remember how helpless i was. i still remember struggling to even believe that this had happend to me. took me a whole 5 years to even admit it to myself that i was harmed. but my body language had changed automatically. anyone trying to even give me a hug i would spaz the eff out. my focus became from trying to achieve my goals where i was a straight a student to only wanting to protect my body
column2: protect myself. saw my grades go down. scholarships being taken away. i didn't realize what was wrong with me. how could i? i was only 16. my brain became from being dedicated to my goals to being dedicated to only protecting myself and my honor and my dignity. i hate even thinking about it because i lose myself in sorrow and dispare but i too should be strong enough to let the world know. even though i was not heard in court when it came down to my daughters custody by a very similar judge like #kavanaugh. i too was shamed and looked over by this so called sham of a justice system. i too am here for the #victims to let them know #metoo i too have survived.  #metoomovement #survivors #survivor;;en;#kavanaugh.

column1: this has been to long in coming and honestly it is time

my hope is for people to realize that mental illness is invisible and you never know who is suffering silently
my hope is for people to realize that we do live in a rape culture

column1: 309538;instagram;2018-10-07 04:38:57;FALSE;"there is nothing more powerful than a insanely large number of angry women (and the men that support them) when they have had enough... when they know they are acting from a place of integrity
column2: a place of truth and justice
column3: and above all there to speak out to protect their daughters
column6: and their grandmothers. we collectively and individually will no longer allow ourselves or our sisters or our grandmothers who have been in this struggle far too long
column10: or otherwise dismissed.  we have been here before
column12: and this time we vow will be the last.

column1: it is not that things will change in one day. it is that in one day
column2: we were all changed. we feel things and therefore will never be the same. the changes we are feeling are unavoidable. we can not go back.

take a deep breath and we begin each and every day from this day forward with all of this in mind.  we are women.  we have stories.  knowing clearly now that we are not alone. we are holding space for each other in such a beautiful way as we share our stories one by one.  we have intuition.  we have a well of love and inner strength.  we have the ability and the vision to take the steps needed to do what needs to be done. we have the right to vote. on every level we will do what needs to be done because that is the only thing we know how to do. i can only assume you know what i mean when i say simply... we are women! we understand in ways we can't possibly put into words.  i am quite sure that all of this
column3: that has somehow been deemed our weaknesses
column4: will in the end be revealed as our greatest superpowers!

column2: individually in our own lives and together for the good of the whole
column3: because that is what we do best. we will take care of ourselves and each other the best we can along the way. we will be gentle with ourselves in moments of vulnerability and push ourselves out of our comfort zones when our voices are needed and when truth needs to be spoken out loud.  we will not be silenced or dismissed. we will rise

column2: what a ride this has been. ❤

column1: my ex raped me. my grandmother died a couple months before. my father called me a whore a day or 2 before her funeral. 3 years later i found myself questioning my value or purpose in living. i wondered how my rapist would react when he saw my lifeless body. i wondered how long it would take him to call my mother. somehow
column2: i didnt transition that night. i got in my honda and put so many miles
column4: and naps in my childhood  bedroom just so i could hear myself process the crumbs i'd tell my sister friends. i still have a hard time describing the psychological warfare i was under during those years in north carolina--in asheville & durham. i found out in july 2012 that he slept with this woman from ga he met up with at a halfway point in al as i was in ms burying my grandmother. that was the day after my father and his childhood friends drove a uhaul truck as me & my mama rode in her car to asheville from oxford. my father was very cruel to me about my decision to live with robert that fall
column5: even doubled down on the way to the funeral.black men panic when they see pieces of their former lives with their daughter. they are hyper aware of the potential danger.

column1: i didnt call my father to pick me up. ""the cow giving away her milk for free"" didnt feel smart or capable enough to. safety felt foreign and far away for 3.5 years. i moved out from robert's sep 2015. i got to dc feb 2016.
for a long time i didnt identify with the term ""survivor
column2: & now i understand  that it's because i was still trying to survive. i wasnt sure if i was gon make it. i had to start talking  in order to. and i love myself so big for refusing to disappear. i'm thankful for all the soft places that let me rest my sword and shield. these are the places i found the value to keep living.

column1: i dance to practice joy in a body where suffering had become habitual within it.

column4: and naps in my childhood  bedroom just so i could hear myself process the crumbs i'd tell my sister friends. i still have a hard time describing the psychological warfare i was under during those years in north carolina--in asheville & durham. i found out in july 2012 that he slept with this woman from ga he met up with at a halfway point in al as i was in ms burying my grandmother. that was the day after my father and his childhood friends drove a uhaul truck as me & my mama rode in her car to asheville from oxford. my father was very cruel to me about my decision to live with robert that fall
column5: even doubled down on the way to the funeral.black men panic when they see pieces of their former lives with their daughter. they are hyper aware of the potential danger.

column1: 309560;instagram;2018-10-07 04:55:13;FALSE;"***trigger warning for survivors of gaslighting/narcissistic abuse*** ""you're 'too sensitive'!""
notice how the person saying these things has no right to dictate how you ""should"" feel!

column2: i became aware of the sociopath-empath-apath triad
column3: and i see it all over now! 😲😲😲 keep this in mind whenever an apathetic person tries to gaslight you out of acknowledging abuse
column4: and setting boundaries for yourself: they are also being abusive. it is the apathy of those who have witnessed (or have been made aware) of the abuse that completes the cycle of objectification (abuse). 🙁

column1: you might have noticed this during the #metoo movement when survivors of sexual assault and violence everywhere began speaking out about the crimes that have been committed against us
column2: and apaths everywhere responded with ""no one cares!""
column4: or ""what were you wearing!?"" it is important to understand that apaths complete the cycle of abuse by agreeing with sociopaths and the more overtly narcissistic abusers that the target of the abuse is an ""object"" who deserves the abuse
column5: or is ""crazy"" or ""must be lying"" about the abuse for ""attention"". the covert gaslighting behavior of apathetic people is more triggering (and even more damaging) than the more overt abuse
column6: because it causes that cognitive dissonance and doubt when someone who seems to be a ""nice"" person is apathetic to our mistreatment. 😕

column2: and note the huge red flag that i am dealing with someone who is demonstrating that they lack empathy.

column1: when apathetic people attempt to gaslight or shame you into accepting abuse
column2: or try to devalue or dismiss you as a person

column1: there might be a possibility that they might be expecting you to accept abuse
column2: because they don't want to be the target of the more overt abuser
column3: but the fact that they are okay with you being the target proves that they simply lack empathy
column4: and empathy can not be taught.

column1: then jaron told me kavanaugh was officially voted and sworn in (i have been off my phone most of today). and i felt this rush of sickness and discouragement and sadness.
and instantly texted my sisters because we’ve been talking about it all.
i took this picture a little over a year ago while visiting the coast. these trees had this beautiful vibrant red flesh beneath their exteriors. this particular tree seemed to be showing its heart.

column3: so many people i know have shown their true selves through their commentary on this hearing.

column1: some i have felt so much connection with; some have made my heart break in confusion of how they could support something that goes so against the values i was raised with.
to any of you who have been dealing with all of the triggering language this past week
i wish we lived in a country that believed women. that didn’t minimize things like sexual assault. that didn’t ascribe to victim blaming.

column1: today was a much needed day of self-care. hearing the news today about #kavanaugh was disheartening

column2: i watched two hours of the trial before i could take no more.  @senatorchuckgrassley interrupting all women. @brettkavanope exhibiting classic tactics of deflection and general hatred towards women. and then @realdonaldtrump mocking a sexual assault victim at a rally. along with countless people chiming in on social media
column4: saying that dr. ford is lying. shitty comments about the #metoo movement. that it's scary to be a man right now and #notallmen and even going as far as hateful words to me about my personal story on #whyididntreport

column1: not to mention all the #survivors coming forward and sharing their stories. it's heartbreaking.
i know you have to squint to see the silver lining
column2: but i'm trying to focus on what i can do
column3: what we can do. i see a whole lot of good people banding together. solidarity. compassion for each other. because we've had enough of this shit. and the election is just a few weeks away now. and please get out there and vote. let's be the change.

column1: 309633;instagram;2018-10-07 04:00:50;FALSE;"in this beyond depressing development i have to keep reminding myself there is hope. if only for my own mental safety. i am reminded of something said after reports of racism escalating post-brexit. it read:"" at least all these people and bigots are standing tall now. for the first time in a while
column2: it means that we know where to aim and shoot"". they are big

column1: 309688;instagram;2018-10-07 03:10:55;FALSE;"it is wonderful that the media is joining in the #metoo campaign. now i have a request to make of every person here. take a closer look at where you work. does your company (startup or mnc) have a clearly laid out policy against harassment? some institutions call it posh (prevention of sexual harassment). it is required by law for every company to have a internal complaints commitee for the same in every organisation ( to the best of my knowledge).. and even if it's not mandatory
column2: it is definitely a great practice to make this a part of your office culture. making this a part of your induction sends out the right message of ""zero tolerance"". the details of the icc (internal complaint committee) should be displayed prominently in company premises and sessions should be conducted to create awareness on what is acceptable behaviour and what is not. people should know the channels to raise complaints.

column1: a word of caution to the startup community... since we are always in a fight for survival
column2: we tend to put these actions on the back burner. don't let that happen here. it is not just a question of this being an ugly affair but also one that is just wrong as far as your human values go.

column1: to the girls out there who have been victims of such incidents at work.. if you keep quiet today
column2: you are responsible for what happens to another girl tomorrow.

column1: 309691;instagram;2018-10-07 03:13:01;FALSE;was i surprised that judge kavanaugh was appointed today? no. no i was not... because this is the way “things” are and this is the way “things” have always been. after all - out of 114 supreme court justices
column2: 108 have been white men (this fact alone cripples me as it transcends more areas of society than the justice system alone). but despite my side lining dissapointment
column3: i know that this is not the way “things” always have to be. last weekend i vomited while taking a shower after reading the @calgaryherald’s column supporting an alleged sexual assailant and i felt utterly betrayed by the woman who wrote it. how lucky is she that she has never experienced the torment and pain that myself and countless others in this city have endured since their sexual assaults. regardless of the nausea i’ve experienced due to this dark time in history... my thoughts are now focused on this: judge kavanaugh has 2 young daughters who i hope will shape the way he views his role and responsibilities as a supreme court justice in the future. we all need to remember that any harmful decision he makes moving forward regarding women’s rights/health will also affect his daughters as they mature and if anyone is going to remember how he treats women moving forward... it’s going to be them. #karmaisabitch #ibelieveher #ibelievewomen #metoo #isurvived #warriorsoul #endrapeoncampus #kavanope #kavanah #sexualabuse #sexualassault #thehuntingground #womenwhorunwithwolves #thebohowolfmommy #yyc #yycnow #yycissues #yycrapeculture #calgary #calgarynow #calgaryissues #calgaryrapeculture;;en;#karmaisabitch

column2: but more motivated than i have ever felt before. today was hard. i am heartbroken today because in confirming kavanaugh
column3: we are sending a message to survivors that it is a real concern that our stories will not be considered or believed by many. i am heartbroken today because i truly thought that we could #blockkavanaugh . i was reminded today
column4: after apologizing for crying during my panel
column5: that it is okay to feel and be emotional right now. we are hurting
column6: and it is okay to feel that as we prepare to stand up again

column1: i never reported what happened to me because i didn’t think anyone would believe me. and unfortunately
column2: in the few times i did try to bring it up
column3: i was told that i didn’t remember enough details or didn’t have enough evidence. watching the kavanaugh hearings was triggering because i felt like all of the responses i had nightmares about hearing if i ever did report

i was in highschool waiting my turn to audition for the talent show. music has always been an important part of my life. especially singing
column2: i had practiced a lot for this audition but if i'm honest i don't recall what song i sang.

column1: when i was waiting in line a guy around my age came up to me and asked me to turn around. i did so and he lifted my skirt up and looked underneath. i don't know how long he held my skirt up for but it felt like forever.
no one really did anything about this
column2: i was shocked that it happened and angry at myself for not screaming or at least smacking him in the face

column1: less than five minutes after this happened
column2: i auditioned for the talent show. i don't remember all the details but i know i was pretty shook up and not at my peak performance even after loads of rehearsing.

column1: i yelled at my dad over nothing on the way home when he picked me up and i stayed in my room crying for the rest of the evening.

i didn't get into the talent show. which was a bummer but i wasn't surprised after what happened. things like this happen every day. i never found out the name of the guy that did this to me but he caused me a great deal of distress. i still consider myself lucky knowing about the abuse so many people have endured.

being a victim of emotional manipulation earlier on in my life i brushed this experience off as not being a big deal. i didn't even bother sharing it a year ago when the #metoo movement began. with the current state of our country as of today i wanted to share my experience because i believe that women and other minorities have voices that matter.
thank you dr. ford for sharing yours.";;en;#metoo

column1: 309722;instagram;2018-10-07 02:04:06;FALSE;"i started therapy this past summer. i was struggling with (what i thought was) a particularly challenging bout of postpartum depression and anxiety...i remember my usually loud
column2: anxious thoughts went quiet. the silence was one of the scariest times of my life. i remember asking god to take it from me
column3: and trying to tell myself that people meditated for years to achieve this kind of stillness 😂  i guess i thought that would make me feel better 🤣

column2: i found myself in therapy confronting my compulsive eating issues right up front.  eating has been my coping mechanism...my security blanket...and my way of burying all the feelings i didn't know how to deal with in the moment. my ""homework"" for the week was to depict the hollow feeling i described to my doctor.

column1: this particular piece was created in photoshop. at the time
column2: i'd been having a hard time drawing just about anything...never mind something so incredibly invasive. looking back
column3: even the color gradient in the background screams of the disconnect happening between my mind and my body.

column1: i'd like to say this picture carried such a breakthrough...but it was more comparable to a ripple as my feet barely skimmed the surface of the depths to come.

column1: 309746;instagram;2018-10-07 02:56:58;FALSE;i posted this picture on facebook a little while ago and i can’t stop staring at it. not because i’m so overwhelmed at how cute casen is (that’s a given)
column2: but because i can’t stop looking at how big my arms are and how i can see my love handles hanging over the top of my skirt. while i’m just as frustrated that i’ve let myself lose the motivation to work out regularly
column3: i’m just as frustrated that i’m putting myself down instead of lifting myself up. it’s hard. being a mom is hard. being a professional is hard. being a working mom is hard. being an adult is hard. staring at a picture (of me and my son) and only being able to see my love handles is so hard. this is your daily reminder that you are enough
column5: you are beautiful and you are allowed to tell yourself that you are. and you’re also allowed to fall apart when you need to. you should be able to take a picture (and a darn cute one) without feeling insecure and too vulnerable to post it because of insecurities of comparison and self doubt. this little boy could care less if my weight is fluctuating (ugh) or if i have the same outfit as the pinterest mom i follow. he just cares that i’m here and that i’m happy. he cares about love. how blessed am i to have this wonderful boy to remind me of that. #metoomovement #metoo #selflove #selfcare #selfportrait #singlemom #workingmom #love #lovewins #itsokaynottobeokay;;en;#metoomovement

column1: 309776;instagram;2018-10-07 02:38:26;FALSE;"i have encountered many things that would qualify as a “metoo” proclamation.
often times we come into a marriage with unresolved “metoo” issues.
until we expose the secret places of victimization and allow god to heal it
column2: there will be barriers of shame
column3: resentment and regret blocking the freedom that one can experience in a marital union.

column1: i come from a broken home #metoo
i had a child out of wedlock #metoo
i felt like walking out on my marriage #metoo
i let betrayal & neglect paralyze me #metoo
i was very insecure and shameful #metoo
i experienced great loss and disappointment #metoo
i will have a healthy & fulfilling marriage #metoo
i can do all things through christ who is my strength #metoo
i will forgive myself for tormenting myself and move forward #metoo
i know my triumphs are greater than my tragedies #metoo
i denounce all the lies spoken over me #metoo
i know god has a plan for my life
i have accomplished so much in spite of #metoo
i will not let fear intimidate me from happiness & success #metoo
i am not suppose to win but i can and i will #metoo * *************************************************
it took time to realize that those negative experiences didn’t define me nor did they disqualify me.  and they did not determine my future. *
ecclesiastes 1:9  what has been will be again
column2: what has been done will be done again; there is nothing new under the sun. (niv)

column3: my heart’s desire is to let you know that you are not the only one.  don’t be fooled by what you see on the outside.  we’ve all had some moments where we thought we weren’t going to bounce back.  the victory comes when we put our confidence in god.

column1: porque queremos que a violência deixe de determinar a experiência do que é ser uma mulher. porque queremos que a violência abandone nossos ossos.
porque não queremos um presidente que diga: “não vou estuprar você porque você é muito feia”

porque não queremos um presidente que defenda que as mulheres devem ganhar menos porque engravidam. porque não queremos um presidente que prefere que o filho morra num acidente de trânsito do que seja homossexual. porque não queremos um presidente que diga que os negros dos quilombos não servem nem para “procriador”. porque não queremos um presidente que defenda a tortura. porque não queremos um presidente que tenha carlos alberto brilhante ustra como herói. porque não queremos um presidente que defenda que a solução para a violência que ele e os seus ajudaram a produzir é armar a população. porque não queremos um presidente que defenda o ódio.

porque não queremos que nossas netas vivam num país governado por um homem que faz sinal de atirar com as mãos. nem queremos que vivam sob o governo de um homem que diz que elas nasceram de uma “fraquejada”.
porque não queremos que as mulheres que nascem agora tenham que viver com medo como nós e nossas filhas vivemos. dos homens que usam pintos como armas e armas como pintos.
porque não queremos que as mulheres sigam sendo vítimas. e votar nele é apertar a tecla de vítima mais uma vez.
porque ser mulher é ter como passado grandes mulheres que lutaram pela liberdade e nos trouxeram até aqui fazendo do nosso corpo rebelião.
porque ser mulher hoje é ter feito a marcha das vadias

column1: but i will not stand down. i will speak my truths while holding myself accountable to listening to counterpoints for the purpose of explaining my stance more adeptly. i will hold space for my anger while acknowledging and learning from the men and women of color who have been fighting battles of justice for ages as opposed to stagnating in my own sense of hopelessness or guilt.
but i will also get rest
column3: and reside in the fact that none of us can fight relentlessly
column4: which is why we find those who will step in when we step briefly out.

column1: 309948;instagram;2018-10-07 01:14:38;FALSE;i don’t know what to say. but i feel like i have to say something. brett kavanaugh’s confirmation as supreme court justice is a slap in the face to women across the globe. it’s a slap in the face to all sexual assault survivors. i’m so fucking angry. there’s this turmoil inside of me and i know i’m not the only one feeling it. i just hope that americans will do the right thing in november and vote for people who don’t treat sexual assault survivors like shit. people who listen and care about what you’ve been through. and i swear if i hear one more person say “why didn’t they report it earlier?” i will fucking punch them. this is why. why? because you dont believe them when they do. why? because you laugh in their face when they do. so why would they? why would they come forward if this is how they’re treated when they do? i just don’t understand. #metoo #believesurvivors #fucktrump #stopkavanaugh;;en;#metoo
